1
00:02:10,165 --> 00:02:13,790
Black cats and goblins
and broomsticks and ghosts.

2
00:02:13,873 --> 00:02:17,123
Covens of witches with all of their hosts.

3
00:02:17,207 --> 00:02:20,499
You may think they scare me,
you're probably right.

4
00:02:20,582 --> 00:02:23,374
Black cats and goblins
on Halloween night.

5
00:02:23,457 --> 00:02:24,831
Trick or treat!

6
00:02:46,415 --> 00:02:48,499
My parents won't be home until 10:00.

7
00:02:48,582 --> 00:02:49,998
- Are you sure?
- Uh-huh.

8
00:02:59,624 --> 00:03:01,873
We are alone, aren't we?

9
00:03:01,957 --> 00:03:03,873
Michael's around some place.

10
00:03:05,290 --> 00:03:06,749
Take off that thing.

11
00:03:09,540 --> 00:03:11,540
- Let's go upstairs.
- Okay.

12
00:03:16,207 --> 00:03:17,873
Your hands are cold.

13
00:04:33,873 --> 00:04:36,749
Look, Judith,
it's really late. I gotta go.

14
00:04:36,831 --> 00:04:38,165
Will you call me tomorrow?

15
00:04:39,249 --> 00:04:41,123
- Yeah, sure.
- Promise?

16
00:04:41,207 --> 00:04:42,207
Yeah.

17
00:05:49,790 --> 00:05:51,165
Michael?

18
00:05:56,040 --> 00:05:57,165
Oh, God!

19
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:32,040
Michael?

20
00:07:46,873 --> 00:07:50,082
Ever done anything like this before?

21
00:07:50,165 --> 00:07:54,290
- Only minimum security.
- I see.

22
00:07:56,040 --> 00:07:58,831
The driveway's
a few hundred yards up on your right.

23
00:08:01,290 --> 00:08:04,207
The only thing that ever bothers me
is their gibberish,

24
00:08:04,290 --> 00:08:08,207
when they start raving on and on.

25
00:08:08,290 --> 00:08:14,082
You don't have anything to worry about.
He hasn't spoken a word in 15 years.

26
00:08:15,165 --> 00:08:17,707
Are there any special instructions?

27
00:08:17,790 --> 00:08:20,957
Just try to understand
what we're dealing with here.

28
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:22,749
Don't underestimate it.

29
00:08:22,831 --> 00:08:25,540
Don't you think we could refer
to it as him?

30
00:08:26,582 --> 00:08:28,957
If you say so.

31
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:32,040
Your compassion's
overwhelming, doctor.

32
00:08:39,207 --> 00:08:42,332
What do I give him when we take him
in front of the judge?

33
00:08:42,415 --> 00:08:43,831
Thorazine.

34
00:08:45,374 --> 00:08:48,666
- He'll barely be able to sit up.
- That's the idea.

35
00:08:58,332 --> 00:09:01,624
- You're serious about it, aren't you?
- Yeah.

36
00:09:04,374 --> 00:09:06,582
You mean you actually never want him
to get out?

37
00:09:06,666 --> 00:09:10,831
Never, never... Never.

38
00:09:10,915 --> 00:09:13,475
Then why are we taking him up
to Hardin County if we just gonna...?

39
00:09:13,499 --> 00:09:15,666
Because that is the law.

40
00:09:17,332 --> 00:09:18,540
Here we are.

41
00:09:24,957 --> 00:09:27,873
Since when did they let them
wander around?

42
00:09:29,415 --> 00:09:30,499
Pull up to the main gate.

43
00:09:30,582 --> 00:09:32,332
- Shouldn't we put...
- Go on, move!

44
00:09:41,749 --> 00:09:42,749
Stop here.

45
00:09:46,540 --> 00:09:48,540
Shouldn't we go on up
to the hospital ins...

46
00:09:48,624 --> 00:09:49,707
Wait.

47
00:10:48,540 --> 00:10:51,582
- Are you all right? You all right?
- Yes, I'm okay.

48
00:10:51,666 --> 00:10:53,666
He's gone. He's gone from here!

49
00:10:53,749 --> 00:10:55,040
The evil is gone!

50
00:11:00,165 --> 00:11:01,749
All right, I got it.

51
00:12:00,582 --> 00:12:02,831
Don't forget to drop off the key off
at the Myers' place.

52
00:12:04,082 --> 00:12:05,207
I won't.

53
00:12:05,290 --> 00:12:07,374
They're coming by to look
at the house at 10:30.

54
00:12:07,457 --> 00:12:10,249
- Be sure you leave it under the mat.
- Promise!

55
00:12:43,499 --> 00:12:44,749
Laurie!

56
00:12:46,499 --> 00:12:48,040
Hi, Tommy.

57
00:12:50,249 --> 00:12:52,998
- Coming over tonight?
- Same time, same place.

58
00:12:53,082 --> 00:12:55,207
- Can we make jack-o'-lanterns?
- Sure.

59
00:12:55,290 --> 00:12:57,415
- Can we watch the monster movies?
- Sure.

60
00:12:57,499 --> 00:12:59,790
Will you read to me?
Can we make popcorn?

61
00:12:59,873 --> 00:13:00,957
Sure, sure, sure.

62
00:13:04,457 --> 00:13:05,915
You better hurry up.

63
00:13:07,290 --> 00:13:09,290
How come you're walking
to school this way?

64
00:13:09,374 --> 00:13:11,749
- My dad asked me to.
- Why?

65
00:13:11,831 --> 00:13:14,207
- I have to drop off a key.
- Why?

66
00:13:14,290 --> 00:13:16,540
- Because he's gonna sell a house.
- Why?

67
00:13:16,624 --> 00:13:19,374
- Because that's his job.
- Where?

68
00:13:19,457 --> 00:13:21,915
- The Myers' house.
- The Myers' house?

69
00:13:31,165 --> 00:13:34,374
- You're not supposed to go up there.
- Yes, I am.

70
00:13:34,457 --> 00:13:38,873
- Uh-uh. That's a spook house.
- Just watch.

71
00:13:48,915 --> 00:13:54,415
Lonnie Elamb said never to go up there.
Lonnie Elamb said that's a haunted house.

72
00:13:54,499 --> 00:13:56,499
He said awful stuff
happened there once.

73
00:13:56,582 --> 00:13:59,457
Lonnie Elamb probably won't get out
of the sixth grade.

74
00:13:59,540 --> 00:14:02,249
I gotta go. I'll see you tonight.

75
00:14:02,332 --> 00:14:03,749
- Bye.
- Bye.

76
00:14:07,457 --> 00:14:11,332
I wish I had you all alone.

77
00:14:12,582 --> 00:14:14,998
Just the two of us.

78
00:14:17,332 --> 00:14:21,831
I would hold you close to me.

79
00:14:21,915 --> 00:14:24,082
So close to me.

80
00:14:27,457 --> 00:14:30,249
Just the two of us.

81
00:14:32,165 --> 00:14:34,415
- I'm not responsible, Sam.
- Oh, no.

82
00:14:34,499 --> 00:14:37,141
- I told them how dangerous he was...
- You could have had two roadblocks

83
00:14:37,165 --> 00:14:39,457
and an all-points bulletin,
it wouldn't stop a 5-year-old.

84
00:14:39,540 --> 00:14:40,725
Well, he was your patient, doctor.

85
00:14:40,749 --> 00:14:42,933
If precautions weren't strong enough,
you should have told somebody.

86
00:14:42,957 --> 00:14:45,831
- I told everybody! Nobody listened.
- There's nothing else I can do.

87
00:14:45,915 --> 00:14:48,058
You could get back there
and get back on the telephone,

88
00:14:48,082 --> 00:14:50,249
tell them exactly who walked
out of here last night,

89
00:14:50,332 --> 00:14:52,998
- and tell them exactly where he's going.
- Probably going.

90
00:14:53,082 --> 00:14:54,165
I'm wasting my time.

91
00:14:54,249 --> 00:14:56,082
Sam, Haddonfield is 150 miles
away from here.

92
00:14:56,165 --> 00:14:57,915
Now, for God's sakes,
he can't drive a car.

93
00:14:57,998 --> 00:14:59,998
He was doing very well last night.

94
00:15:00,082 --> 00:15:03,666
Maybe someone around here
gave him lessons.

95
00:15:06,582 --> 00:15:10,207
Dr. Chance, please report to Ward C.

96
00:15:10,290 --> 00:15:14,457
Dr. Chance, Ward C, please.

97
00:15:14,540 --> 00:15:17,582
And the book ends.

98
00:15:17,666 --> 00:15:23,499
But what Samuels is really talking
about here is fate.

99
00:15:24,582 --> 00:15:30,873
You see, fate caught up
with several lives here.

100
00:15:30,957 --> 00:15:35,207
No matter what course of action
Collins took,

101
00:15:35,290 --> 00:15:38,957
he was destined to his own fate,

102
00:15:39,040 --> 00:15:42,207
his own day of reckoning with himself.

103
00:15:43,374 --> 00:15:48,207
The idea is that destiny

104
00:15:48,290 --> 00:15:54,415
is a very real, concrete thing
that every person has to deal with.

105
00:15:54,499 --> 00:15:59,207
How does Samuels' view of fate
differ from that of Costain's?

106
00:15:59,290 --> 00:16:00,415
Laurie?

107
00:16:00,499 --> 00:16:02,457
- Ma'am?
- Answer the question.

108
00:16:02,540 --> 00:16:08,040
Oh, um, Costain wrote that fate
was somehow related only to religion,

109
00:16:08,123 --> 00:16:11,332
whereas Samuels felt that, well,
fate was like a natural element,

110
00:16:11,415 --> 00:16:13,499
like earth, air, fire and water.

111
00:16:13,582 --> 00:16:17,040
That's right.
Samuels definitely personified fate.

112
00:16:17,123 --> 00:16:21,290
In Samuels' writing,
fate is immovable, like a mountain.

113
00:16:21,374 --> 00:16:24,749
It stands where man passes away.

114
00:16:24,831 --> 00:16:26,707
Fate never changes.

115
00:16:45,957 --> 00:16:47,540
- Yeah.
- Stupid pumpkin.

116
00:16:47,624 --> 00:16:50,790
- Yeah, how's the little witches?
- Yeah, stupid pumpkin.

117
00:16:50,873 --> 00:16:51,957
Leave me alone.

118
00:16:52,040 --> 00:16:53,540
He's gonna get you.

119
00:16:53,624 --> 00:16:58,207
He's gonna get you,
he's gonna get you...

120
00:16:58,290 --> 00:16:59,707
The boogeyman is coming.

121
00:16:59,790 --> 00:17:01,790
- Leave me alone!
- He doesn't believe us.

122
00:17:01,873 --> 00:17:04,207
Don't you know what happens
on Halloween?

123
00:17:04,290 --> 00:17:06,165
Yeah, we get candy.

124
00:17:07,415 --> 00:17:08,957
The boogeyman, ooh, the boogeyman.

125
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:11,790
The boogeyman,
the boogeyman, the boogeyman...

126
00:18:45,790 --> 00:18:48,666
He's on his way.

127
00:18:48,749 --> 00:18:52,290
You've gotta believe me, officer.
He is coming to Haddonfield.

128
00:18:53,624 --> 00:18:56,582
Because I know him.

129
00:18:56,666 --> 00:18:59,249
I'm his doctor.
You must be ready for him.

130
00:19:01,165 --> 00:19:02,790
If you don't, it's your funeral.

131
00:19:54,998 --> 00:19:56,998
We're from Haddonfield,
couldn't be prouder.

132
00:19:57,082 --> 00:19:59,499
Can't hear us now,
we'll yell a little louder.

133
00:19:59,582 --> 00:20:01,749
We're from Haddonfield,
couldn't be prouder...

134
00:20:01,831 --> 00:20:04,540
Oh, look at you!
Look all the books you have.

135
00:20:04,624 --> 00:20:07,290
You need a shopping cart to get home.

136
00:20:08,415 --> 00:20:11,957
- Hey, Haddonfield!
- Yeah, not funny.

137
00:20:13,915 --> 00:20:15,165
You know, it's totally insane.

138
00:20:15,249 --> 00:20:17,457
We have three new cheers
to learn in the morning,

139
00:20:17,540 --> 00:20:20,249
the game is in the afternoon,
I have to get my hair done at 5:00,

140
00:20:20,332 --> 00:20:22,749
and the dance is at 8:00.
I'll be totally wiped out!

141
00:20:22,831 --> 00:20:24,225
I don't think you have enough
to do tomorrow.

142
00:20:24,249 --> 00:20:25,457
Totally.

143
00:20:30,915 --> 00:20:32,998
As usual, I have nothing to do.

144
00:20:33,082 --> 00:20:35,998
It's your own fault
and I don't feel a bit sorry for you.

145
00:20:37,332 --> 00:20:39,082
Hey, Lynda, Laurie!

146
00:20:40,082 --> 00:20:41,540
Why didn't you wait for me?

147
00:20:41,624 --> 00:20:44,499
We did. Fifteen minutes,
you totally never showed.

148
00:20:44,582 --> 00:20:46,915
That's not true. Here I am.

149
00:20:49,540 --> 00:20:51,165
What's wrong, Annie?
You're not smiling.

150
00:20:51,249 --> 00:20:53,207
I'm never smiling again.

151
00:20:53,290 --> 00:20:56,082
Paul dragged me
into the boys' locker room to tell me...

152
00:20:56,165 --> 00:20:57,457
Exploring uncharted territory?

153
00:20:57,540 --> 00:20:59,540
- It's been totally charted.
- We just talked.

154
00:20:59,624 --> 00:21:00,998
- Sure, sure.
- Sure. Mm-hmm.

155
00:21:01,082 --> 00:21:04,207
Old jerk-o got caught throwing eggs
and soaping windows.

156
00:21:04,290 --> 00:21:07,332
His parents grounded him.
He can't come over tonight.

157
00:21:07,415 --> 00:21:08,998
I thought
you were babysitting tonight.

158
00:21:09,082 --> 00:21:11,082
Only reason she babysits
is to have a place...

159
00:21:11,165 --> 00:21:15,249
- Shit.
- I have a place for that.

160
00:21:15,332 --> 00:21:17,790
I forgot my chemistry book.

161
00:21:17,873 --> 00:21:19,998
So who cares? I always forget
my chemistry book.

162
00:21:20,082 --> 00:21:23,998
And my math book, and my English book,
and my, let's see, my French book and...

163
00:21:24,082 --> 00:21:27,915
Oh, who needs books anyway? I don't need
books, I always forget all of my books.

164
00:21:27,998 --> 00:21:30,998
I mean, it doesn't really matter if you
have your books or not.

165
00:21:32,582 --> 00:21:34,582
Hey, isn't that Devon Graham?

166
00:21:36,249 --> 00:21:38,082
I don't think so.

167
00:21:38,165 --> 00:21:39,873
I think he's cute.

168
00:21:44,123 --> 00:21:46,040
Hey, jerk!

169
00:21:46,123 --> 00:21:48,165
Speed kills!

170
00:21:58,499 --> 00:22:01,082
God, can't you take a joke?

171
00:22:08,290 --> 00:22:11,090
You know, Annie, someday, you're going
to get us all into deep trouble.

172
00:22:14,082 --> 00:22:15,374
Totally.

173
00:22:15,457 --> 00:22:18,666
I hate a guy with a car
and no sense of humor.

174
00:22:21,540 --> 00:22:23,582
Well, are we still on for tonight?

175
00:22:23,666 --> 00:22:26,457
I wouldn't wanna get you
in deep trouble, Lynda.

176
00:22:26,540 --> 00:22:30,707
Oh, come on, Annie! Bob and I
have been planning on it all week.

177
00:22:30,790 --> 00:22:34,457
All right. The Wallaces leave at 7:00.

178
00:22:34,540 --> 00:22:35,873
I'm babysitting the Doyles.

179
00:22:35,957 --> 00:22:38,141
It's only three houses down.
We can keep each other company.

180
00:22:38,165 --> 00:22:40,915
Oh, terrific. I've got three choices.

181
00:22:40,998 --> 00:22:44,790
Watch the kid sleep, listen to Lynda
screw around, or talk to you.

182
00:22:48,666 --> 00:22:50,957
I am so mad.

183
00:23:17,831 --> 00:23:19,207
Why don't you buy your own then?

184
00:23:19,290 --> 00:23:21,457
You bummed 20 off me, girl.

185
00:23:22,457 --> 00:23:24,749
- What time tonight?
- I don't know yet.

186
00:23:24,831 --> 00:23:26,933
I have to get out of taking
my little brother trick-or-treating.

187
00:23:26,957 --> 00:23:30,123
- Saving the treats for Bob?
- Funny. See you.

188
00:23:30,207 --> 00:23:32,790
- Bye.
- Bye.

189
00:23:44,957 --> 00:23:47,790
- Annie, look.
- Look where?

190
00:23:47,873 --> 00:23:49,332
Behind the bush.

191
00:23:50,915 --> 00:23:51,915
I don't see anything.

192
00:23:51,998 --> 00:23:54,207
The guy who drove by so fast,
the one you yelled at?

193
00:23:55,207 --> 00:23:57,207
Oh, subtle, isn't he?

194
00:24:04,207 --> 00:24:05,415
Hey, creep.

195
00:24:09,082 --> 00:24:12,123
Laurie, dear, he wants to talk to you.

196
00:24:13,123 --> 00:24:15,666
He wants to take you out tonight.

197
00:24:30,207 --> 00:24:31,873
He was standing right there.

198
00:24:31,957 --> 00:24:36,374
Poor Laurie!
You scared another one away.

199
00:24:36,457 --> 00:24:38,873
It's tragic. You never go out.

200
00:24:38,957 --> 00:24:42,540
You must have a small fortune stashed
from babysitting so much.

201
00:24:42,624 --> 00:24:44,123
Guys think I'm too smart.

202
00:24:44,207 --> 00:24:47,915
I don't, I think you're whacko.
Now you're seeing men behind bushes.

203
00:24:50,707 --> 00:24:53,707
Well, home sweet home.

204
00:24:53,790 --> 00:24:55,707
See you later.

205
00:24:55,790 --> 00:24:58,290
- Bye.
- Bye.

206
00:25:12,165 --> 00:25:13,831
- Excuse me, Laurie.
- Oh, Mr. Brackett!

207
00:25:13,915 --> 00:25:14,998
I'm sorry, Mr. Brackett.

208
00:25:15,082 --> 00:25:17,499
- Oh, I didn't mean to startle you.
- Oh, it's all right.

209
00:25:17,582 --> 00:25:19,624
You know, it's Halloween.

210
00:25:19,707 --> 00:25:21,683
I guess everyone's entitled
to one good scare, huh?

211
00:25:21,707 --> 00:25:25,082
Yes, sir. Nice seeing you, sir.

212
00:25:47,040 --> 00:25:48,499
Oh, no.

213
00:25:57,666 --> 00:25:59,624
No.

214
00:26:03,499 --> 00:26:05,374
- Trick or treat.
- Trick or treat.

215
00:26:10,040 --> 00:26:13,540
Well, kiddo,
I thought you outgrew superstition.

216
00:27:02,165 --> 00:27:03,582
Hello.

217
00:27:07,207 --> 00:27:08,749
Hello?

218
00:27:10,707 --> 00:27:12,374
Who is this?

219
00:27:22,374 --> 00:27:25,040
- Hello?
- Why'd you hang up on me?

220
00:27:25,123 --> 00:27:28,040
- Annie? Was that you?
- Of course.

221
00:27:28,123 --> 00:27:30,249
Why didn't you say anything?
You scared me to death.

222
00:27:30,332 --> 00:27:32,290
I had my mouth full.
Couldn't you hear me?

223
00:27:32,374 --> 00:27:34,040
Thought it was an obscene phone call.

224
00:27:34,123 --> 00:27:37,374
Now you hear obscene chewing.
You're losing it, Laurie.

225
00:27:37,457 --> 00:27:39,624
- I already lost it.
- I doubt that.

226
00:27:39,707 --> 00:27:43,207
Listen, my mother is letting me
use her car. I'll pick you up, 6:30.

227
00:27:43,290 --> 00:27:45,332
- Okay, bye.
- Bye.

228
00:27:57,790 --> 00:27:59,831
Just calm down.

229
00:28:00,831 --> 00:28:02,582
This is ridiculous.

230
00:29:18,249 --> 00:29:20,957
- Hurry up.
- Hi.

231
00:29:29,332 --> 00:29:31,831
We just have time.

232
00:29:42,915 --> 00:29:46,332
Yeah, Judith Myers. Myers...

233
00:29:47,540 --> 00:29:51,332
"Row 18, plot 20."

234
00:29:51,415 --> 00:29:55,666
Yeah, you know, you know, every town
has something like this happen.

235
00:29:55,749 --> 00:30:01,123
I remember over in Russellville,
old Charlie Bowles, about 15 years ago.

236
00:30:01,207 --> 00:30:07,040
One night, he finished dinner,
and excused himself from the table.

237
00:30:07,123 --> 00:30:10,040
And he went out to the garage.

238
00:30:10,123 --> 00:30:13,165
He got himself a hacksaw.

239
00:30:13,249 --> 00:30:15,290
And then he went back into the house,

240
00:30:15,374 --> 00:30:18,540
and he kissed his wife
and his two children goodbye,

241
00:30:18,624 --> 00:30:19,749
and then he proceeded...

242
00:30:19,831 --> 00:30:21,415
- Where are we?
- Huh?

243
00:30:21,499 --> 00:30:24,582
Oh, it's right over here.

244
00:30:24,666 --> 00:30:28,040
Yeah, Myers, Judith Myers.
I remember her.

245
00:30:28,123 --> 00:30:31,290
Couldn't believe it.
Such a young boy.

246
00:30:32,290 --> 00:30:34,749
What's the matter, are you lost?

247
00:30:34,831 --> 00:30:37,998
Why do they do it? Goddamn kids!

248
00:30:39,998 --> 00:30:42,998
They'll do anything for Halloween.

249
00:30:43,082 --> 00:30:46,582
- Whose grave is it?
- Oh, I don't know. Uh...

250
00:30:46,666 --> 00:30:48,831
Eighteen, 19...

251
00:30:51,499 --> 00:30:53,040
Judith Myers.

252
00:30:56,082 --> 00:30:58,040
He came home.

253
00:31:02,582 --> 00:31:06,499
- You still spooked?
- I wasn't spooked.

254
00:31:06,582 --> 00:31:08,540
- Lies.
- I wasn't!

255
00:31:08,624 --> 00:31:10,582
I saw somebody standing
in Mr. Riddle's backyard.

256
00:31:10,666 --> 00:31:13,207
- Probably Mr. Riddle.
- He was watching me.

257
00:31:13,290 --> 00:31:16,915
Mr. Riddle was watching you?
Laurie, Mr. Riddle is 87!

258
00:31:16,998 --> 00:31:19,915
- He can still watch.
- That's probably all he can do.

259
00:31:21,207 --> 00:31:23,415
- What's the pumpkin for?
- I brought it for Tommy.

260
00:31:23,499 --> 00:31:26,540
I figured carving a jack-o'-lantern
would keep him occupied.

261
00:31:26,624 --> 00:31:29,332
I always said
you'd make a fabulous Girl Scout.

262
00:31:29,415 --> 00:31:30,499
Thanks.

263
00:31:30,582 --> 00:31:33,290
And for that matter, I might as well
be a Girl Scout myself tonight.

264
00:31:33,374 --> 00:31:36,540
I plan on making popcorn
and watching Dr. Dementia.

265
00:31:36,624 --> 00:31:38,915
Six straight hours of horror movies.

266
00:31:38,998 --> 00:31:41,332
Little Lindsey Wallace
won't know what hit her.

267
00:31:51,374 --> 00:31:54,123
My dad! Get rid of this.

268
00:32:02,082 --> 00:32:03,998
Laurie, stop coughing.

269
00:32:04,082 --> 00:32:06,249
- What's the matter with you?
- Jesus!

270
00:32:06,332 --> 00:32:09,624
Just be natural. There he is.
Just be natural, Laurie.

271
00:32:14,666 --> 00:32:16,249
Hi, Annie, Laurie.

272
00:32:16,332 --> 00:32:19,040
- Hi.
- Hi, Dad, what happened?

273
00:32:19,123 --> 00:32:21,040
- What?
- What happened?

274
00:32:21,123 --> 00:32:24,749
Oh, uh, somebody broke
into the hardware store. Probably kids.

275
00:32:24,831 --> 00:32:26,915
You blame everything on kids.

276
00:32:26,998 --> 00:32:29,249
Well, all they took
was some Halloween masks,

277
00:32:29,332 --> 00:32:32,374
a rope, and a couple of knives.
Now, who do you think it was?

278
00:32:32,457 --> 00:32:36,040
It's hard growing up
with a cynical father.

279
00:32:36,123 --> 00:32:37,915
- Aren't you gonna be late?
- Huh?

280
00:32:37,998 --> 00:32:40,249
I said aren't you gonna be late?!

281
00:32:40,332 --> 00:32:42,207
He shouts too.

282
00:32:45,831 --> 00:32:47,332
Bye, girls.

283
00:32:47,415 --> 00:32:49,374
- Bye, Dad.
- Bye.

284
00:32:57,207 --> 00:32:59,249
Sheriff?

285
00:32:59,332 --> 00:33:02,249
Pardon me, I'm, uh, Loomis.
Dr. Sam Loomis.

286
00:33:02,332 --> 00:33:03,415
Uh, Lee Brackett.

287
00:33:03,499 --> 00:33:05,058
I'd like to have a word
with you if I could.

288
00:33:05,082 --> 00:33:08,374
- Maybe a few minutes. I gotta take care...
- It's important.

289
00:33:08,457 --> 00:33:10,332
- Ten minutes.
- I'll be here.

290
00:33:26,499 --> 00:33:28,499
What's the matter with you?

291
00:33:28,582 --> 00:33:30,666
I think he knew.
I'm sure he could smell it.

292
00:33:30,749 --> 00:33:34,082
- No, he didn't.
- He did. See the look on his face?

293
00:33:34,165 --> 00:33:36,998
He always looks like that.

294
00:33:40,290 --> 00:33:42,123
What are you gonna wear
to the dance tomorrow?

295
00:33:42,207 --> 00:33:44,707
I didn't know you thought
about things like that, Laurie.

296
00:33:51,707 --> 00:33:54,082
- You know, you could ask somebody.
- Oh, I couldn't.

297
00:33:54,165 --> 00:33:57,499
Sure you could. All you have to do
is go up to somebody and say:

298
00:33:57,582 --> 00:33:59,831
"You wanna go to the dance?"

299
00:33:59,915 --> 00:34:02,749
You could do that. I couldn't.

300
00:34:02,831 --> 00:34:06,040
Well, you could ask Dick Baxter.
He'd go out with you.

301
00:34:06,123 --> 00:34:08,457
I'd rather go out with Ben Tramer.

302
00:34:09,915 --> 00:34:13,915
Ben Tramer? I knew it!

303
00:34:15,624 --> 00:34:18,249
So you do think about
things like that, huh, Laurie?

304
00:34:19,624 --> 00:34:21,749
- Shut up.
- He's cute.

305
00:34:21,831 --> 00:34:24,415
- Ben Tramer.
- Shh.

306
00:34:56,831 --> 00:34:57,915
Okay.

307
00:35:30,666 --> 00:35:32,290
Trick or treat, trick or treat.

308
00:35:32,374 --> 00:35:34,123
Give me something good to eat.

309
00:35:34,207 --> 00:35:37,873
Trick or treat, trick or treat,
give me something good to eat...

310
00:35:53,082 --> 00:35:54,415
- Hi.
- Hi, Annie. Come on in.

311
00:35:59,332 --> 00:36:01,040
Uh, be in bed by 9:00, Lindsey, okay?

312
00:36:01,123 --> 00:36:02,915
- Have a good night, dear.
- Be a good girl.

313
00:36:02,998 --> 00:36:04,540
- Bye-bye.
- See you.

314
00:36:05,998 --> 00:36:07,873
- Take care.
- Okay.

315
00:36:30,540 --> 00:36:34,082
- Does anybody live here?
- No, not since 1963, when it happened.

316
00:36:34,165 --> 00:36:36,666
Every kid in Haddonfield thinks
this place is haunted.

317
00:36:36,749 --> 00:36:38,290
They may be right.

318
00:36:56,165 --> 00:36:58,249
- Look.
- What?

319
00:36:58,332 --> 00:36:59,707
What is that?

320
00:36:59,790 --> 00:37:02,290
It's a dog.

321
00:37:07,957 --> 00:37:10,499
Still warm.

322
00:37:10,582 --> 00:37:12,290
He got hungry.

323
00:37:13,499 --> 00:37:16,957
- Come on. It could've been a skunk.
- Could have.

324
00:37:18,666 --> 00:37:22,582
- A man wouldn't do that.
- This isn't a man.

325
00:37:58,831 --> 00:38:00,915
It happened in here.

326
00:38:00,998 --> 00:38:03,499
She was sitting right here.

327
00:38:11,249 --> 00:38:12,929
He could have seen her
through this window.

328
00:38:15,207 --> 00:38:17,831
Standing on the lawn,
he could have seen inside.

329
00:38:26,831 --> 00:38:30,915
Huh, you must think me
a very sinister doctor.

330
00:38:32,165 --> 00:38:34,957
Oh, um, I do have a permit.

331
00:38:37,499 --> 00:38:39,957
Seems to me you're just plain scared.

332
00:38:40,040 --> 00:38:41,957
Yes. Yeah, I am, uh...

333
00:38:43,873 --> 00:38:48,249
I met him 15 years ago.
I was told there was nothing left.

334
00:38:48,332 --> 00:38:50,998
No reason, no, uh, conscience,

335
00:38:51,082 --> 00:38:54,957
no understanding in even the most
rudimentary sense of life or death,

336
00:38:55,040 --> 00:38:59,873
of good or evil,
of right or wrong.

337
00:38:59,957 --> 00:39:05,707
I met this 6-year-old child
with this blank, pale,

338
00:39:05,790 --> 00:39:11,123
emotionless face,
and the blackest eyes.

339
00:39:12,207 --> 00:39:14,831
The devil's eyes.

340
00:39:14,915 --> 00:39:17,666
I spent eight years trying to reach him.

341
00:39:17,749 --> 00:39:20,082
And then another seven trying
to keep him locked up,

342
00:39:20,165 --> 00:39:23,332
because I realized that what was living
behind that boy's eyes

343
00:39:23,415 --> 00:39:26,082
was purely and simply evil.

344
00:39:27,415 --> 00:39:29,415
What do we do?

345
00:39:29,499 --> 00:39:33,666
He's been here once tonight.
I think he'll come back.

346
00:39:33,749 --> 00:39:35,374
I'm gonna wait for him.

347
00:39:35,457 --> 00:39:37,391
I still think I should notify
the radio and television...

348
00:39:37,415 --> 00:39:40,831
No. If you do that, they'll see him
on every street corner,

349
00:39:40,915 --> 00:39:42,165
look for him in every house.

350
00:39:42,249 --> 00:39:45,915
Just tell your men to keep
their mouths shut and their eyes open.

351
00:39:48,873 --> 00:39:50,624
I'll check back in an hour.

352
00:40:01,957 --> 00:40:03,499
"'How now, ' cried Arthur.

353
00:40:03,582 --> 00:40:06,332
'Let no one pass this way
without a fight.'

354
00:40:06,415 --> 00:40:10,165
'Is that so?, ' said the knight,
in a bold and haughty manner."

355
00:40:10,249 --> 00:40:13,998
- I don't like that story.
- I thought King Arthur was your favorite.

356
00:40:14,082 --> 00:40:15,624
Not anymore.

357
00:40:17,915 --> 00:40:21,957
- Why do you keep them under there?
- Mom doesn't like me to have them.

358
00:40:22,040 --> 00:40:24,290
"Laser Man."

359
00:40:24,374 --> 00:40:27,499
"Neutron Man." I can understand why.

360
00:40:27,582 --> 00:40:29,374
"Tarantula Man."

361
00:40:29,457 --> 00:40:32,165
Laurie, what's the boogeyman?

362
00:40:38,831 --> 00:40:40,707
Doyle residence.

363
00:40:40,790 --> 00:40:42,666
- It's me.
- Hi, Annie, what are you doing?

364
00:40:42,749 --> 00:40:44,374
Making popcorn.

365
00:40:44,457 --> 00:40:49,290
Having fun?
Never mind, I'm sure you are.

366
00:40:49,374 --> 00:40:51,666
I have big, big news for you.

367
00:40:54,915 --> 00:40:56,790
Oops. Hold on a minute.

368
00:40:58,332 --> 00:41:00,249
Hi, Lester.

369
00:41:00,332 --> 00:41:02,998
I'm about to be ripped apart
by the family dog.

370
00:41:08,707 --> 00:41:12,624
Lindsey, get this dog out
of the kitchen right now.

371
00:41:23,332 --> 00:41:27,123
I hate that dog. I'm the only person
in the world he doesn't like.

372
00:41:27,207 --> 00:41:30,290
So, what is this big, big news?

373
00:41:30,374 --> 00:41:31,831
What would you say if I told you

374
00:41:31,915 --> 00:41:34,873
that you were going to the homecoming
dance tomorrow night?

375
00:41:35,998 --> 00:41:37,600
I'd probably say
you have the wrong number.

376
00:41:37,624 --> 00:41:42,415
Well... I just talked with Ben Tramer,

377
00:41:42,499 --> 00:41:46,957
and he got real excited when I told him
how attracted you were to him.

378
00:41:47,040 --> 00:41:51,457
Oh, Annie! Oh, you didn't.
Please tell me you didn't.

379
00:41:51,540 --> 00:41:54,707
How could you do that?
I mean, how can you just call him...

380
00:41:55,957 --> 00:41:58,374
What do you mean it was easy?

381
00:41:58,457 --> 00:42:00,207
I can't believe this.

382
00:42:00,290 --> 00:42:02,374
I can't tell you anything.

383
00:42:02,457 --> 00:42:05,624
Every time I tell you something,
everyone else knows about it.

384
00:42:06,624 --> 00:42:08,749
No, I'm not mad.

385
00:42:08,831 --> 00:42:12,540
Please tell me you didn't.
Oh, you didn't.

386
00:42:12,624 --> 00:42:14,624
- Laurie.
- Oh, I'm so embarrassed.

387
00:42:14,707 --> 00:42:17,332
- The boogeyman is outside.
- I couldn't even face him.

388
00:42:17,415 --> 00:42:19,374
- Laurie, he's out there.
- Hold on.

389
00:42:19,457 --> 00:42:21,957
Laurie, the boogeyman
is outside. Look.

390
00:42:27,915 --> 00:42:31,831
Tommy, there's nobody outside.
Go watch TV.

391
00:42:31,915 --> 00:42:34,123
It's just Tommy.

392
00:42:34,207 --> 00:42:37,915
Oh, please, tell me you didn't.
How could you do that?

393
00:42:37,998 --> 00:42:39,998
Look, it's simple.

394
00:42:40,082 --> 00:42:43,873
You like him, he likes you.
All you need is a little push.

395
00:42:45,165 --> 00:42:48,499
Well, it won't hurt you to go out
with him, for God's sake!

396
00:42:48,582 --> 00:42:49,582
Shit!

397
00:42:50,749 --> 00:42:53,831
No, no, I just made a mess of myself.
I gotta call you back.

398
00:42:53,915 --> 00:42:58,123
Oh, yuck!
Lindsey, I need a robe!

399
00:43:04,873 --> 00:43:08,582
Little creep.

400
00:43:42,249 --> 00:43:46,666
Lindsey, Lester's barking again
and getting on my nerves again.

401
00:43:50,666 --> 00:43:54,082
Oh, never mind.
I guess he found a hot date.

402
00:44:42,831 --> 00:44:46,332
- What about the jack-o'-lantern?
- After the movie.

403
00:44:46,415 --> 00:44:49,790
- What about the rest of my comic books?
- After the jack-o'-lantern.

404
00:44:49,873 --> 00:44:53,207
- And what about the boogeyman?
- There's no such thing.

405
00:44:53,290 --> 00:44:55,249
Richie said
he was coming after me tonight.

406
00:44:55,332 --> 00:44:57,123
Do you believe everything
Richie tells you?

407
00:44:57,207 --> 00:44:58,957
No.

408
00:44:59,040 --> 00:45:03,040
Tommy, Halloween night... it's
when people play tricks on each other.

409
00:45:03,123 --> 00:45:05,831
It's all make-believe. I think Richie
was just trying to scare you.

410
00:45:05,915 --> 00:45:09,582
I saw the boogeyman. I saw him outside.

411
00:45:09,666 --> 00:45:11,415
There was nobody outside.

412
00:45:11,499 --> 00:45:14,915
- There was.
- What did he look like?

413
00:45:14,998 --> 00:45:16,332
The boogeyman.

414
00:45:17,582 --> 00:45:19,790
We're not getting anywhere.

415
00:45:19,873 --> 00:45:23,123
All right. The boogeyman can only
come out on Halloween night, right?

416
00:45:23,207 --> 00:45:25,082
- Right.
- Well, I'm here tonight.

417
00:45:25,165 --> 00:45:27,332
I'm not about to let
anything happen to you.

418
00:45:27,415 --> 00:45:30,873
- Promise?
- Promise.

419
00:45:30,957 --> 00:45:35,499
- Can we make the jack-o'-lantern now?
- Let's go.

420
00:45:57,165 --> 00:45:59,582
Hmm, terrific.

421
00:46:17,499 --> 00:46:18,499
Hello?

422
00:46:19,624 --> 00:46:21,666
Who's there?

423
00:46:23,582 --> 00:46:26,957
Paul, is this one of your cheap tricks?

424
00:46:30,290 --> 00:46:31,666
Guess not.

425
00:46:32,998 --> 00:46:35,499
No tricks for Annie tonight.

426
00:46:50,957 --> 00:46:52,123
Come on.

427
00:46:53,123 --> 00:46:54,249
Lindsey!

428
00:46:55,624 --> 00:46:57,165
Lindsey, come out here!

429
00:46:57,249 --> 00:47:01,165
Lindsey, I'm in the laundry room.
The door won't open.

430
00:47:01,249 --> 00:47:04,790
Spread out, everybody. We're gonna try
to figure out the shape of this thing.

431
00:47:05,790 --> 00:47:07,499
Holy cats.

432
00:47:07,582 --> 00:47:09,957
- Hey.
- Yeah.

433
00:47:10,040 --> 00:47:11,873
Almost a perfect...

434
00:47:13,998 --> 00:47:16,790
- We finally got one.
- We found a flying saucer.

435
00:47:16,873 --> 00:47:19,998
Oh, Lindsey,
get the phone! It's Paul!

436
00:47:20,998 --> 00:47:25,457
Lindsey! Lindsey!

437
00:47:35,165 --> 00:47:37,415
Please hold. I'm here.

438
00:47:44,249 --> 00:47:45,415
Oh, excellent.

439
00:47:45,499 --> 00:47:48,040
- Where do you figure it's from?
- I don't know.

440
00:47:48,123 --> 00:47:49,207
Hello?

441
00:47:49,290 --> 00:47:51,666
Hi, Lindsey, this is Paul.
Is Annie there?

442
00:47:51,749 --> 00:47:54,415
- Yes, she is.
- Get her for me, will you?

443
00:47:54,499 --> 00:47:58,374
- She's washing her clothes.
- Look, just tell her it's me, okay?

444
00:47:58,457 --> 00:48:00,040
Okay.

445
00:48:05,290 --> 00:48:07,165
Annie, Paul called!

446
00:48:20,207 --> 00:48:22,873
- You locked yourself in.
- I know!

447
00:48:25,207 --> 00:48:27,457
Pull my foot. I'm stuck.

448
00:48:46,290 --> 00:48:49,582
Now, promise me
you won't tell anybody about this.

449
00:49:08,415 --> 00:49:11,457
She got stuck in the window.
She'll be right here.

450
00:49:13,873 --> 00:49:15,666
- Hello.
- Hi, Annie.

451
00:49:15,749 --> 00:49:18,082
- Oh, hi, Paul.
- Stuck, huh?

452
00:49:18,165 --> 00:49:20,873
All right, cut it out.
It can happen to anyone.

453
00:49:20,957 --> 00:49:22,624
Sure, stuck in the window.

454
00:49:22,707 --> 00:49:26,165
Yeah, but I've seen you stuck
in plenty of other positions.

455
00:49:26,249 --> 00:49:27,666
My parents are gone.

456
00:49:27,749 --> 00:49:30,457
Oh, that's fabulous.
When did they leave?

457
00:49:30,540 --> 00:49:31,624
About a half-hour ago.

458
00:49:31,707 --> 00:49:35,207
Oh, utterly fantastic.

459
00:49:35,290 --> 00:49:38,332
- So why don't you just walk over?
- You come and pick me up.

460
00:49:38,415 --> 00:49:40,707
Oh, I can't come now.
My clothes are in the wash.

461
00:49:40,790 --> 00:49:43,415
- You won't need them.
- Oh, shut up, jerk.

462
00:49:43,499 --> 00:49:46,707
God, I've got a shirt on.
That's all you ever think about.

463
00:49:46,790 --> 00:49:48,666
I think that's all you ever think about.

464
00:49:48,749 --> 00:49:50,540
That's no true.
I think about lots of things.

465
00:49:50,624 --> 00:49:52,707
Now why don't we not stand here
talking about them

466
00:49:52,790 --> 00:49:55,082
and get down to doing them?

467
00:49:55,165 --> 00:49:59,499
Lock your doors,
bolt your windows

468
00:49:59,582 --> 00:50:02,582
and turn off the lights.

469
00:50:02,666 --> 00:50:05,374
Don't go away,
because here's a scene from...

470
00:50:05,457 --> 00:50:06,582
I'm scared.

471
00:50:06,666 --> 00:50:08,957
Then why are you sitting here
with all the lights off?

472
00:50:09,040 --> 00:50:10,880
- I don't know.
- Well, come on, get your coat.

473
00:50:10,957 --> 00:50:14,290
- We're going to pick up Paul.
- I don't want to.

474
00:50:14,374 --> 00:50:17,123
Look, Lindsey,
I thought we understood each other.

475
00:50:17,207 --> 00:50:19,249
I wanna stay here and watch this.

476
00:50:19,332 --> 00:50:20,499
Okay.

477
00:50:20,582 --> 00:50:24,540
Well, if I can fix it so you can watch TV
with Tommy Doyle, would you like that?

478
00:50:24,624 --> 00:50:26,998
- Yeah.
- Well, come with me.

479
00:50:31,915 --> 00:50:34,165
Come on, hurry up!

480
00:51:03,831 --> 00:51:05,290
Hi, Tommy.

481
00:51:05,374 --> 00:51:08,332
Hi, come on in.
We're making a jack-o'-lantern.

482
00:51:08,415 --> 00:51:11,915
- You know, I wanna watch TV.
- How would you like that, kiddies?

483
00:51:11,998 --> 00:51:13,374
- Good.
- Annie, I'm in here.

484
00:51:13,457 --> 00:51:19,873
And now, the horrifying conclusion
to The Thing.

485
00:51:22,207 --> 00:51:25,249
- All fancy.
- This has not been my night.

486
00:51:27,415 --> 00:51:30,123
I spilled butter all over my clothes,
they're in the wash.

487
00:51:30,207 --> 00:51:32,016
- I got stuck in the laundry room.
- Let me tell you something.

488
00:51:32,040 --> 00:51:34,725
I'd like you to call Ben Tramer and tell
him that you were just fooling around.

489
00:51:34,749 --> 00:51:36,123
- I can't.
- Yes, you can.

490
00:51:36,207 --> 00:51:39,332
No, he went drinking with Mike Godfrey
and he won't be back till late.

491
00:51:39,415 --> 00:51:41,998
You'll have to call him tomorrow.

492
00:51:42,082 --> 00:51:45,457
Besides, I'm on my way to pick up Paul.

493
00:51:45,540 --> 00:51:46,624
Wait a minute...

494
00:51:46,707 --> 00:51:51,998
If you watch her, I'll consider
talking to Ben Tramer in the morning.

495
00:51:52,082 --> 00:51:54,040
Deal.

496
00:51:54,123 --> 00:51:55,683
- I thought Paul was grounded.
- He was.

497
00:51:55,707 --> 00:51:57,915
Old jerk-o found a way to sneak out.

498
00:51:57,998 --> 00:52:00,457
Listen, I'll call you
in an hour or so, okay?

499
00:52:00,540 --> 00:52:01,624
Yeah.

500
00:52:01,707 --> 00:52:03,249
- Bye.
- Bye.

501
00:52:07,290 --> 00:52:09,790
The old Girl Scout
comes through again.

502
00:52:22,540 --> 00:52:26,415
My Paul, I give you all...

503
00:52:29,082 --> 00:52:34,707
No keys, but please, my Paul.

504
00:53:05,165 --> 00:53:10,749
Oh, Paul, I can no longer stall.

505
00:53:10,831 --> 00:53:12,790
Oh, Paul.

506
00:53:12,873 --> 00:53:18,249
Oh, Paul, I can no longer stall.

507
00:53:18,332 --> 00:53:21,290
Dear Paul.

508
00:53:23,499 --> 00:53:25,332
My Paul.

509
00:54:20,831 --> 00:54:23,915
Attention, Captain to crew.
Stand by to reverse polarity.

510
00:54:23,998 --> 00:54:27,957
Standard class-A security
will be maintained upon landing.

511
00:54:28,040 --> 00:54:31,790
And until further notice, all hands
will wear sidearms. That is all.

512
00:54:31,873 --> 00:54:34,499
- Artificial gravity off.
- Aft locked.

513
00:54:34,582 --> 00:54:36,666
- Cut primary coils.
- Primary's cut, sir.

514
00:55:01,123 --> 00:55:02,749
Lindsey.

515
00:55:02,831 --> 00:55:06,957
- Lindsey.
- Where are you?

516
00:55:32,207 --> 00:55:33,540
Hey, it's the boogeyman!

517
00:55:33,624 --> 00:55:36,415
He's outside! The boogeyman's outside!

518
00:55:36,499 --> 00:55:38,499
- Look, there's the boogeyman!
- What's wrong?

519
00:55:38,582 --> 00:55:41,141
- I saw the boogeyman. He's at Lindsey's...
- Oh, Tommy, stop it.

520
00:55:41,165 --> 00:55:43,666
- You're scaring Lindsey.
- He's outside! He's over there at...

521
00:55:43,749 --> 00:55:46,540
Tommy, stop it!
Now, there's nobody out there.

522
00:55:46,624 --> 00:55:48,915
There's no boogeyman,
and if you don't stop all this,

523
00:55:48,998 --> 00:55:50,915
I'm gonna turn off the TV
and send you to bed.

524
00:55:55,082 --> 00:55:59,207
- Nobody believes me.
- I believe you, Tommy.

525
00:56:31,790 --> 00:56:33,540
- I'm not afraid.
- Bull.

526
00:56:33,624 --> 00:56:36,123
- I'm not.
- Then go in.

527
00:56:43,082 --> 00:56:45,998
- Chicken!
- Go ahead, Lonnie.

528
00:56:47,165 --> 00:56:48,457
Go in!

529
00:56:51,624 --> 00:56:52,666
Hey.

530
00:56:53,749 --> 00:56:57,290
Hey, Lonnie.
Get your ass away from there.

531
00:57:09,624 --> 00:57:10,707
Jesus.

532
00:57:10,790 --> 00:57:13,707
- Are you all right?
- Yeah.

533
00:57:13,790 --> 00:57:16,290
Nothing's going on
except kids playing pranks,

534
00:57:16,374 --> 00:57:19,540
trick-or-treating,
parking, getting high.

535
00:57:19,624 --> 00:57:21,624
I have the feeling
that you're way off on this.

536
00:57:21,707 --> 00:57:23,540
You have the wrong feeling.

537
00:57:23,624 --> 00:57:25,600
Well, you're not doing very much
to prove me wrong.

538
00:57:25,624 --> 00:57:27,207
What more do you need?

539
00:57:27,290 --> 00:57:29,123
Well, it's gonna take
more than fancy talk

540
00:57:29,207 --> 00:57:31,457
to keep me up all night,
crawling around these bushes.

541
00:57:31,540 --> 00:57:36,249
I watched him for 15 years,
sitting in a room, staring at a wall,

542
00:57:36,332 --> 00:57:39,165
not seeing the wall,
looking past the wall,

543
00:57:39,249 --> 00:57:42,165
looking at this night,
inhumanly patient.

544
00:57:44,540 --> 00:57:50,040
Waiting for some secret silent alarm
to trigger him off.

545
00:57:50,123 --> 00:57:53,624
Death has come
to your little town, sheriff.

546
00:57:53,707 --> 00:57:57,332
You can either ignore it
or you can help me to stop it.

547
00:57:57,415 --> 00:58:01,415
More fancy talk. Doctor,
do you know what Haddonfield is?

548
00:58:01,499 --> 00:58:05,707
Families, children, all lined up in rows
up and down these streets.

549
00:58:05,790 --> 00:58:08,040
You're telling me
they're lined up for a slaughterhouse.

550
00:58:08,123 --> 00:58:10,957
They could be.

551
00:58:11,040 --> 00:58:15,457
All right, I'll stay with you tonight,
just on the chance that you're right.

552
00:58:15,540 --> 00:58:19,207
And if you are right,
damn you for letting him go.

553
00:58:40,707 --> 00:58:42,207
Okay, so we're gonna...

554
00:58:42,290 --> 00:58:44,624
First we go inside, right?
Then we'll just talk a little.

555
00:58:44,707 --> 00:58:45,849
Then Annie will distract Lindsey,

556
00:58:45,873 --> 00:58:48,540
that's when we go upstairs,
to the first bedroom on the left.

557
00:58:48,624 --> 00:58:51,707
- You got it?
- Okay, first I rip your clothes off.

558
00:58:51,790 --> 00:58:54,123
No, don't rip my blouse.
It's expensive, idiot.

559
00:58:54,207 --> 00:58:56,915
Then you rip my clothes off.
Then we rip Lindsey's clothes off.

560
00:58:56,998 --> 00:58:59,290
- Yeah, I think I got it.
- Totally.

561
00:59:14,915 --> 00:59:16,540
No, no!

562
00:59:19,249 --> 00:59:21,831
Bob, put me down!

563
00:59:21,915 --> 00:59:24,624
Put me down! This is totally silly!

564
00:59:24,707 --> 00:59:25,707
Put me down!

565
00:59:29,040 --> 00:59:31,207
- Hey, it's totally dark.
- Yeah.

566
00:59:32,290 --> 00:59:33,998
Hey, Annie!

567
00:59:34,082 --> 00:59:37,457
- Annie, we're here!
- I wonder where they went.

568
00:59:37,540 --> 00:59:40,831
Oh, Annie probably took Lindsey out
for something.

569
00:59:48,957 --> 00:59:51,707
- Hey, let's look for a note.
- Let's don't.

570
01:00:26,249 --> 01:00:28,915
- He's gonna get you.
- No, he's not.

571
01:00:28,998 --> 01:00:31,499
Hey, nobody's getting anybody.
Stop scaring each other.

572
01:00:47,707 --> 01:00:50,957
Everybody's having a good time tonight.

573
01:00:51,040 --> 01:00:53,957
- All right, you guys, what's next?
- Let's make more popcorn.

574
01:00:54,040 --> 01:00:56,831
No, we've had enough.
Why don't we watch the rest of the movie?

575
01:00:56,915 --> 01:00:58,415
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

576
01:01:15,415 --> 01:01:16,749
Doyle house.

577
01:01:16,831 --> 01:01:18,666
Hi, Laurie. What's up?

578
01:01:18,749 --> 01:01:21,040
Uh, I'm just sitting down
for the first time tonight.

579
01:01:22,290 --> 01:01:23,831
Hey, is Annie around?

580
01:01:23,915 --> 01:01:26,374
No. I thought she'd be home by now.
She went to pick up Paul.

581
01:01:26,457 --> 01:01:29,207
Well, she's totally not here.

582
01:01:30,415 --> 01:01:33,332
She probably stopped off some place.
Have her call me when she gets home.

583
01:01:33,415 --> 01:01:36,415
I have Lindsey here and I wanna know
what time to put her to bed.

584
01:01:36,499 --> 01:01:39,915
- Okay. Later.
- Have a good time.

585
01:01:39,998 --> 01:01:42,040
We definitely will.

586
01:01:43,082 --> 01:01:44,332
Bye.

587
01:01:46,082 --> 01:01:50,707
- Lindsey is gone for the night.
- Hey, now that's wonderful!

588
01:02:34,165 --> 01:02:36,123
Oh, shit. Not again.

589
01:02:36,207 --> 01:02:38,707
I can't help it. The phone keeps ringing.

590
01:02:38,790 --> 01:02:42,165
- Oh, and I can't keep you interested?
- Just answer the damn phone.

591
01:02:42,249 --> 01:02:44,582
Well, I can't. What if it's the Wallaces?

592
01:02:44,666 --> 01:02:46,666
We'd get Annie in trouble, you know.

593
01:02:50,666 --> 01:02:52,082
Just take it off the hook.

594
01:03:26,040 --> 01:03:28,915
Oh, fantastic.

595
01:03:31,707 --> 01:03:33,915
- Totally.
- Yeah.

596
01:03:43,165 --> 01:03:45,624
- Want a beer?
- Yeah.

597
01:03:45,707 --> 01:03:48,790
- Is that all you can say?
- Yeah.

598
01:03:51,249 --> 01:03:54,290
- Go get me a beer.
- I thought you were gonna get me one.

599
01:03:54,374 --> 01:03:55,540
Yeah?

600
01:03:57,957 --> 01:04:01,790
I'll be right back.
Don't get dressed.

601
01:04:57,582 --> 01:04:58,749
Annie?

602
01:04:59,957 --> 01:05:01,165
Paul?

603
01:05:04,790 --> 01:05:06,540
Lynda, you asshole!

604
01:05:11,290 --> 01:05:13,790
Okay, Lynda. Come on out.

605
01:06:16,415 --> 01:06:18,290
Well, did you get my beer?

606
01:06:25,082 --> 01:06:27,207
Cute, Bob. Real cute.

607
01:06:39,582 --> 01:06:42,249
See anything you like?

608
01:06:49,123 --> 01:06:51,499
What's the matter?
Can't I get your ghost, Bob?

609
01:07:00,040 --> 01:07:02,457
All right, all right.
Come on, where's my beer?

610
01:07:08,374 --> 01:07:10,082
Well, can't you answer me?

611
01:07:14,332 --> 01:07:15,957
Okay, don't answer me.

612
01:07:17,415 --> 01:07:18,957
Boy, are you weird.

613
01:07:19,040 --> 01:07:23,123
Well, I'm gonna call Laurie.
I wanna know where Paul and Annie are.

614
01:07:23,207 --> 01:07:24,957
This is going nowhere.

615
01:07:28,957 --> 01:07:30,374
Finally.

616
01:07:36,165 --> 01:07:37,165
Hello?

617
01:07:40,499 --> 01:07:41,790
Hello?

618
01:07:44,415 --> 01:07:45,457
All right, Annie.

619
01:07:45,540 --> 01:07:48,415
First, I get your famous chewing,
now I get your famous squealing?

620
01:07:52,790 --> 01:07:55,332
Annie, are you all right?

621
01:08:04,082 --> 01:08:06,165
Are you fooling around again?

622
01:08:07,749 --> 01:08:09,415
I'll kill you if this is a joke.

623
01:08:10,415 --> 01:08:11,998
Annie?

624
01:08:14,499 --> 01:08:15,499
Annie?

625
01:09:04,915 --> 01:09:06,499
Sleep tight, kids.

626
01:12:16,624 --> 01:12:18,165
Bob?

627
01:12:19,582 --> 01:12:20,831
Lynda?

628
01:12:28,915 --> 01:12:30,165
Lynda?

629
01:12:41,499 --> 01:12:42,831
Annie?

630
01:13:00,499 --> 01:13:01,749
Annie?

631
01:13:04,998 --> 01:13:06,374
Lynda?

632
01:13:08,540 --> 01:13:09,790
Bob?

633
01:13:25,374 --> 01:13:26,915
All right, Annie.

634
01:13:51,790 --> 01:13:54,249
All right, meatheads. Joke's over.

635
01:13:58,666 --> 01:14:00,749
Come on, Annie. It's enough.

636
01:14:04,831 --> 01:14:07,415
This most definitely stopped
being funny. Now, cut it out!

637
01:14:11,082 --> 01:14:12,582
You'll be sorry.

638
01:16:58,207 --> 01:16:59,666
Oh, God!

639
01:17:23,749 --> 01:17:25,123
Oh. No.

640
01:17:37,290 --> 01:17:38,290
Help.

641
01:17:45,499 --> 01:17:46,707
No.

642
01:17:51,624 --> 01:17:55,666
Help! Somebody help me, please!

643
01:17:55,749 --> 01:17:57,749
Somebody help!

644
01:17:57,831 --> 01:18:00,374
Oh, God, help me!

645
01:18:00,457 --> 01:18:03,249
Please! Please help me!

646
01:18:05,666 --> 01:18:07,873
Help!

647
01:18:07,957 --> 01:18:10,415
Oh, God, help me, please!

648
01:18:10,499 --> 01:18:12,499
Hello! Hello!

649
01:18:15,457 --> 01:18:17,165
Hello, help me!

650
01:18:17,249 --> 01:18:20,790
Can you please help me?! Please!

651
01:18:20,873 --> 01:18:23,998
Can't you hear me?
Oh, God!

652
01:18:27,082 --> 01:18:29,873
Help me, please!

653
01:18:41,332 --> 01:18:43,831
The keys! Oh, the keys!

654
01:18:49,332 --> 01:18:53,249
Tommy! Tommy, it's me!

655
01:18:55,582 --> 01:18:56,582
Tommy!

656
01:19:06,123 --> 01:19:08,290
- Who is it?
- Tommy, open up, it's me!

657
01:19:08,374 --> 01:19:09,749
Yeah, okay.

658
01:19:09,831 --> 01:19:11,332
Tommy, please!

659
01:19:12,624 --> 01:19:14,123
Tommy, hurry up!

660
01:19:14,207 --> 01:19:16,249
Tommy, please!

661
01:19:17,374 --> 01:19:21,332
Tommy! Hurry up!

662
01:19:21,415 --> 01:19:22,998
Tommy, please!

663
01:19:23,082 --> 01:19:24,499
- Tommy, get upstairs.
- What is it?

664
01:19:24,582 --> 01:19:25,849
Get upstairs, get Lindsey,
lock the bedroom door.

665
01:19:25,873 --> 01:19:27,415
- I'm scared!
- Do as I say!

666
01:19:27,499 --> 01:19:29,040
- The boogeyman...
- Hurry!

667
01:19:41,207 --> 01:19:42,707
Oh, no.

668
01:19:57,831 --> 01:19:59,290
Please stop.

669
01:19:59,374 --> 01:20:00,624
Please.

670
01:21:15,499 --> 01:21:17,707
Where were you?
I went to the Myers' house...

671
01:21:17,790 --> 01:21:19,540
I found the car. He's here.

672
01:21:19,624 --> 01:21:21,040
- Where?
- He's three blocks down.

673
01:21:21,123 --> 01:21:24,082
You go around the back of the houses.
I'll watch the front.

674
01:21:24,165 --> 01:21:25,499
- Go on!
- All right.

675
01:21:55,499 --> 01:21:57,249
Tommy? Lindsey?

676
01:21:59,624 --> 01:22:00,998
Babies.

677
01:22:04,831 --> 01:22:07,957
- We're gonna take a little walk.
- Was it the boogeyman?

678
01:22:08,040 --> 01:22:10,749
- I'm scared.
- There's nothing to be scared of.

679
01:22:10,831 --> 01:22:14,082
Are you sure? How?

680
01:22:15,332 --> 01:22:19,540
- I killed him.
- You can't kill the boogeyman.

681
01:22:22,957 --> 01:22:25,123
Get in there, come on, Tommy!
Now lock the door!

682
01:25:03,540 --> 01:25:06,082
Tommy, unlock the door.

683
01:25:09,666 --> 01:25:12,624
Come here.
Now, just listen to me.

684
01:25:13,624 --> 01:25:16,249
I want you to go down the stairs
and out the front door.

685
01:25:16,332 --> 01:25:19,374
I want you to go down the street
to the Mackenzies' house.

686
01:25:19,457 --> 01:25:23,582
I want you to tell them to call the police
and tell them to send them over here.

687
01:25:23,666 --> 01:25:25,225
- Laurie...
- Now, do you understand me?

688
01:25:25,249 --> 01:25:27,624
- Yes.
- Go, do as I say.

689
01:25:48,582 --> 01:25:50,082
Come on! Get help!

690
01:25:50,165 --> 01:25:52,998
Come on. Come on!

691
01:27:16,749 --> 01:27:18,707
It was the boogeyman.

692
01:27:24,123 --> 01:27:26,749
As a matter of fact, it was.

